## Conclusion and Key Findings

This study developed and evaluated three recommendation approaches: content-based filtering, collaborative filtering using SVD, and a hybrid model combining both techniques. The results indicate that the SVD-based collaborative filtering model achieved the best overall performance, with the lowest prediction error (RMSE = 0.3378, MAE = 0.0947) and excellent ranking quality (Precision@5 = 0.9163, Recall@5 = 0.6086, NDCG@5 = 0.9897).

In contrast, the content-based filtering model performed significantly worse, with higher error values (RMSE = 0.9087, MAE = 0.7119) and lower ranking performance (Precision@5 = 0.5187, Recall@5 = 0.3207, NDCG@5 = 0.6857). This suggests that relying solely on content features was not sufficient to effectively capture user preferences in this dataset.

The hybrid model showed a slight improvement in ranking performance when α = 0.7 (Precision@5 = 0.9183, NDCG@5 = 0.9900), but this came at the cost of reduced prediction accuracy (RMSE = 0.4125). Further tuning revealed that the optimal configuration was α = 1.0, which effectively reduced the hybrid model to the SVD model. This indicates that the content-based component did not provide additional useful information in this case.

Overall, the findings demonstrate that collaborative filtering using SVD is the most effective approach for this dataset, as it provides both high prediction accuracy and strong recommendation quality. Future work could focus on improving the richness and quality of content features, such as incorporating more detailed metadata or advanced text representations, to enhance the effectiveness of hybrid recommendation systems.

